<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-07-1057 </DOCNO><TEXT>Over the past two decades, several new imaging modalities have emergedand revolutionized the diagnostic approach to several branches of medicineand disease processes. Ultrasound, computed tomography, digital subtractionangiography, and magnetic resonance imaging have emerged and become standardtools to both the radiologist and clinician. The purpose of this chapteris to review the legal literature regarding these relatively new subspecialties.While little has been written on their medicolegal implications, it isonly a matter of time before they provide as familiar a basis of negligentmalpractice as the older techniques.</TEXT></DOC>